The Index is like a large 53 Pick List .  You can use the four arrow keys,
and the PgUp and PgDn keys.

To select a new Topic, just highlight the entry and press Enter.

If you want to return to the previous Topic, just press the Alt-F1 key.
!TOPIC 119 Capture File Toggle (^Home)

This allows you to open a Capture File to save all the text displayed on
your screen to a file on a disk.

The first time you press ^Home, you will be prompted for a filename to save
the data to.  Any valid DOS filename will do nicely.  When you are done
capturing data, just press ^Home a second time to close the file.
!Topic 4 Translate Table Selection (Alt-A)
!Noindex

Qmodem maintains two separate tables; Input for incoming characters, and
Output for outgoing characters.

Choose the translate table you wish to modify, or press ESC to return to
Terminal Mode.

See also: 7 Editing Characters in the Table 
!Topic 7 Editing Characters in the Table
!NoIndex
The Edit Window for both tables is the same.  Across the top of the window
you have a display of the currently selected entry showing the original
character and what it will be replaced with.

Below that is the actual table.  Because Qmodem supports changing all 256
characters, only half of each table is shown at a time.  The current
character is highlighted and boxed in with the [ and ] characters.  As
you use the Arrow keys, this will move to select a different character to
change.

If you have already changed one or more characters, you will notice that they
too are highlighted.  This is a visual cue to quickly show you which ones
have been changed.

The Status Line shows the following options:

[] Movement   Arrow keys that move the Box Cursor around.

[S] Swap   Swaps the screen for the hidden half of the character set.

[Spacebar] Change   This prompt for the new Character value (in decimal)

[F10] Save   A very important key!  You must use this to save any
changes you make!

[ESC] Exit   Leave the screen.


Changing an Entry

Move the half-box cursor to the desired ASCII value/character you want to
strip or replace.  The number to the left is the original ASCII value; the
number on the right is the translated character.

Press the Spacebar once.  A prompt like this will appear:

          Enter new value for 0 >  0°°

To strip the character, replace the value with a 0 (zero).  Any other value
acts as a translation.

Press ENTER to complete the change.  Don't forget to use F10 to save
the changes you make!
!Topic 8 Edit Prefixes (Alt-D/E)
!Noindex

Qmodem allows up to 10 Prefix codes, lettered A-J, to be defined.  Each
Prefix can store up to 30 characters.  

The term Prefix can be a little misleading.  Prefix characters can be used
at the beginning or end of phone numbers and anywhere in between to add
standard and repetitive dialing information to the numbers as they are
dialed.

A Prefix may be as simple as Dial 9 to get out, or it may hold a 7-digit
Sprint or MCI local access number.  When the Prefix is stored at the end of a
number, it may be used to store a PBX Access code.  In one special case, it
can even be used to store an alternate Modem Dial Prefix (Alt-N/M/M/P)
command.

The window uses a 9 Multi-Field Editor .  You do not need to select the
entry before you start making changes.  Just use the Up/Down arrow keys (or
the Enter key) to move down the list.  When you are finished making changes,
press F10 to save them to the QMODEM.PRE file, or ESC to abort any
changes made.

TIP: One of the most asked- questions about the dialing directory is how to
get an MNP modem to switch modes on-the-fly when dialing entries.  Here's how
you do it!

For this example, the USRobotics Courier HST Dual Standard will be used.  The
HST uses the &M command to control whether or not MNP is used.

   Step 1:  Set Alt-N/M/M/P to AT&M4DT.  This makes the default mode to
            use MNP data compression for every call.

   Step 2:  Define a Prefix character (we will use A in this example) 
            to AT&M0DT.  This will be used with the special Prefix
            modifier character ` (left tick mark) to tell the Redialer
            NOT to use the default Alt-N/M/M/P string.

   Step 3:  For every number in your phone book that you do NOT want to
            use MNP, you will add `A as a Prefix in the number field.
            This is how you override the default.

   Done!

This technique can be used for just about any modem command, and is not
limited to the setting of MNP.  Turning on and off the Modem Speaker is
another popular command that fits this scenario.  Just add the extra commands
between the AT and the DT in both strings.  The possibilities are endless.
