!Topic 41 Setup/Protocols/Toggles
!Noindex

The Protocol toggles control various actions in uploading and downloading.

The first two toggles, Overwrite Files and Auto-Increment Filename work
in tandem to control how downloaded files are treated.  The rules are not
that complicated and will be discussed in detail.  One of the combinations
will be the right one for you.

NOTE: To keep confusion to a minimum, the exception to the rule is the Zmodem
protocol and will be discussed at the end.  (smile)

When you are prompted for a filename in one of the download protocols, a
check is made to see if the file already exists.  If it does, the Auto-
Increment flag is checked.  If it is set ON, then the filename entered gets
incremented (see 88 Filename Increment Rules  for more details) and the
transfer begins.

If the Auto-Increment flag is set OFF, then the Overwrite Files flag is
checked.  If this is set ON, the existing file is deleted and the transfer
begins.  If it is set OFF, then you will be prompted for a different
filename before the transfer can begin.
!Page

The exception to the rule:

When downloading using any protocol except Zmodem (yes, there is always an
exception to the rule), the Auto-Increment flag is checked first, and then
the Overwrite flag.  With Zmodem, there is another possibility called Crash
Recovery.  This will override the above mentioned flags under certain
specific conditions.

First we need to explain the Save Partials flag.  A Partial is created when
the Save Partials flag is set ON and a download aborts. The portions that
have been received successfully are not deleted.  If it is set OFF, then any
partially downloaded file is erased when the transfer aborts.

If the file you are downloading already exists and the file on disk is
smaller than the one being downloaded, there is a possibility that the file
on disk is a Partial.  Zmodem then attempts to use Crash Recovery to pick up
where the you left off.

If it turns out that the two files are not the same, then the original
rules apply.  IE. A check of the Auto-Increment flag, and then the Overwrite
if Auto-Increment is OFF.  If Overwrite is also OFF, the file is SKIPPED by
the Zmodem download.

Whew...  That should cover all the possibilities.

Clear Batch Screen  This is the only toggle that deals with Uploads.  All
the others affect Downloads.  One of the new features in Qmodem is support
for Batch Uploads.  The Batch Entry Window (BEW) has the ability to retain
the entered information so you can do the same batch upload to several
different systems without retyping the entire BEW screen.

When a Batch upload completes, this flag is checked to see if the BEW
information should be cleared.  The default is ON.  Even if you leave this
set OFF, you can still clear the old information in the BEW with a press of
the F4 key.

Zmodem Autostart When this parameter is ON, Zmodem file downloads are
started automatically whenever a Zmodem download transfer header is received.
If this parameter is OFF, Zmodem downloads must be started manually with the
PgDn command.
!Topic 88 Filename Increment Rules
!Noindex
When it is necessary to increment the filename, the following rules are
applied:
                 FILENAME.EXT
                 ---+---- -+-
                    |      |
          NAME -----+      +--- EXTENSION

TOP OF THE TESTS:
!Line
The NAME portion is first checked to see if all 8 characters have been
declared.  If the length is less than 8 characters, a 0 is added to the
NAME portion, the new filename is checked to see if one exists, and if so a
loops back to the top of the tests.

If the NAME portion has all 8 characters defined, the last character is
incremented and another test to see if the new filename is unique.  If not,
then back to the top again.

Now, if all the characters are exhausted by twiddling the 8th character, the
7th character is twiddled, then the 6th, the 5th and so on....  Eventually, a
unique filename WILL be generated!
