!Topic 130 Status Line Toggle (Alt-Minus)

Alt-Minus toggles the Status Line on and off.  This is most useful when
used in combination with the 131 Doorway Keyboard Emulation .

If you turn the status line off, the current terminal emulation in effect has
one additional line to work with.  This can be the difference between a
perfect display and one that seems to self-destruct.
!Topic 131 Doorway Keyboard Emulation (Alt-Equal)

Doorway mode is a special keyboard emulation.  Instead of sending sets of
ESC codes to tell the remote what you want to do, the entire PC Keyboard Scan
Code set is used.  These are the same codes that a normal program running on
the PC would see.  If the remote system is capable of translating these "scan
codes", then you have the keyboard emulator!

On the PC side, there is a program called DOORWAY.EXE that is bundled with
the Qmodem Host mode.  This program gives the host a method of dropping to
DOS and running any program (in text mode) from remote!  With Qmodem (in
DoorWay mode) and the remote running the DOORWAY program, you can do all
sorts of things that would take hundreds of dollars to do with commercial
software!

In some cases, remote software may already be "Doorway Aware" but not support
the enhanced 101 key keyboard extended E0 codes.  These can be disabled in
Qmodem with the Alt-N/O/T/0 Setup switch.  If you see a funny à code
while running in Doorway mode, then set this switch OFF.

NOTE:  The only key that cannot be pressed in DoorWay mode, is the Alt-= key.
This is the toggle for Doorway mode.
