!Topic 123 Video 43/50-Line mode (Alt-4)

If you have an EGA, or greater video card, this will switch the screen into
80x43 (EGA) or 80x50 (VGA, MCGA) mode.  The advantages are that you will have
a larger screen to view.  

Some operations in Qmodem will also take advantage of the larger screen size;
for instance, the Alt-D will display twice as many entries, filename Pick
Lists will be taller, and much more.

It should be noted, that you are not limited to just Alt-2 and Alt-4.  If
your video card supports SuperEGA or SuperVGA and can be programmed into one
of a dozen different display modes, just do it before starting up Qmodem! 
The current video mode detected at startup will be used automatically!
!Topic 124 Host Mode (Alt-5)

The Alt-5 command activates the built-in Host mode.  Effectively, Host mode
turns Qmodem into a mini Bulletin Board System, complete with Electronic
Mail, File Transfers, and Sysop Chat capabilities.  The Host provides simple
features and is not intended to compete with full-featured BBS software
packages such as Wildcat!.

The Host requires setup of additional parameters with the Alt-N function,
including system type, user time allowance, Sysop passwords, host-specific
modem commands, and up/download file directories. External files for Host
Menus, Online Help Files and User Passwords are also required and can be
created with the Full Screen Editor or your favorite ASCII text editor.

Please refer to the Qmodem documentation for complete details on setting up
and using the Host.  This is out of the scope of this Help Entry.
!Topic 127 8th Bit Toggle (Alt-8)

The 8th Bit toggle is used to decide whether or not to strip the 8th data bit
of incoming text data.  Each byte has 8 bits, and the 8th bit is used by some
systems as the PARITY bit.  

If you were to call a mainframe system that was set up as 7-E-1, and your
modem was set for 8-N-1, the text from the mainframe may display as
gobbledegook.  This is because the 8th bit from the mainframe is being used
as a parity bit, but your PC thinks all 8 bits are to be used as valid data.
When a system is set for 7-E-1 (or 7-O-1 too), only the first 7 bits are used
to form valid data.

So, if this parity problem arises, you have two choices:

1.  Hang up, reset your phone book entry to 7-E-1 (or whatever the other
system thinks you should be using).   -or-

2.  Hit the Alt-8 combination to tell Qmodem to strip the 8th bit (the parity
bit) before trying to make sense out of the data.  This will allow the text
to display normally.
!Page

NOTE: Ideally, the first option should be used.  While Qmodem is fully
capable of stripping the 8th bit on incoming data, this does NOT mean that
the 8th bit is converted correctly going out.  Only by correctly matching all
the parameters (Data bits, Parity and Stop bits) are you assured of a clean
session.
!Topic 128 Printer Echo Toggle (Alt-9)

Alt-9 toggles the printer echo.  When ON, all screen data is sent to the
current default printer (usually LPT1:).  

Prior to using this command, make SURE the printer is connected and ready. 
If not, the system will display the "Retry, Ignore or Fail" error window.  

If Alt-9 was pressed by accident, reply "F" to cancel the DOS print request. 
If the printer was not connected or was not ready, correct the problem and
reply "R" to start printing.
!Topic 93 Filename Pick List
!NoIndex

This Pick List window allows you to move the Scrollbar to select a filename
for the preceding function.

In addition, you can use Speed Search.  Speed Search is as easy as typing
in characters of the target filename.  As you type, the Pick List searches
for the first filename that matches what you have entered so far.  The lower
left corner of the window border will keep track of the characters you have
entered.  When a character is entered that no longer can match any files, the
Speed Search buffer is flushed.

The status line has the following options:

Arrows-Scroll  Means you can use the Arrow keys to move the Scrollbar to
select the filename.

Alpha-Search  The Speed Search we just discussed.

Enter-Selects  Press the Enter key to select the filename in the
Scrollbar.

ESC-Exit  Closes the Filename Pick List window without selecting a
filename.

If the Search window allows choosing a different subdirectory, the following
option will also show on the status line:

<dir>-Change Directory  This allows changing the current search directory
to a new directory on the same Drive.  It does not allow moving to a
different drive. (not yet anyway)
!Topic 94 Baud Rate Selection
!Noindex

Use the Up/Down Arrow keys to move the scrollbar to the desired baud rate.

Press Enter to select, or ESC to exit the Pick Window.
!Topic 95 CR handling
!Noindex

Use the Up/Down Arrow keys to move the scrollbar to the desired action to be
taken when handling the CR character.

NONE  Exactly that...  nothing happens.

STRIP  The CR character is stripped from the data stream.  As if it never
existed.

ADD LF  After the CR, a LINEFEED (LF) will be added to the data stream.

Press Enter to select, or ESC to exit the Pick Window.
!Topic 96 LINEFEED (LF) Handling
!Noindex

Use the Up/Down Arrow keys to move the scrollbar to the desired action to be
taken when handling the LF character.

NONE  Exactly that...  nothing happens.

STRIP  The LF character is stripped from the data stream.  As if it never
existed.

ADD LF  Before the LF, a Carriage Return (CR) will be added to the data
stream.

Press Enter to select, or ESC to exit the Pick Window.
!Topic 97 Sort Selection
!Noindex

There are 3 possible ways to Sort the FON book:

1 - Name (ascending)  This sorts all entries by the NAME field in ascending
order.  Ascending is from A to Z.  This is not case sensitive.

2 - Number (ascending)  This sorts by the NUMBER field.  Again, in
ascending order.

3 - Total Calls (descending)  This sorts by the Total calls field.  By
sorting in descending order, the entries you call most frequently will
float to the top of the list.  Thus, next time you press Alt-D, your 10
most called entries are right there!  (The author's personal favorite.)

To select one, either move the scrollbar with the arrow keys, or press 1,2 or
3 and then press ENTER.  ESC to exit the Pick Window and not sort the FON
book.

Remember, you can always use the ^U Undo command if you really didn't want
to sort the FON book.
!Topic 98 Stop Bits Selection 
!Noindex

Use the Up/Down Arrow keys to move the scrollbar to the desired Stop Bits.

Press Enter to select, or ESC to exit the Pick Window.

NOTE: Unless explicitly told otherwise, you should use a value of 1.
!Topic 99 Data Bits Selection
!Noindex

Use the Up/Down Arrow keys to move the scrollbar to the desired Data Bits.

Press Enter to select, or ESC to exit the Pick Window.

NOTE: It is a good idea to change the Parity to NONE if you are using 8 data
bits and to either EVEN or ODD if you select 7 data bits.
!Topic 100 Parity Selection
!Noindex

Use the Up/Down Arrow keys to move the scrollbar to the desired Parity.

Press Enter to select, or ESC to exit the Pick Window.

NOTE: It is a good idea to change the Data Bits to 8 if you select NONE as a
Parity.  Any other value and you should change Data Bits to 7.
!Topic 28 Manual Dial  (Alt-D/M)
!NoIndex

Manual dialing allows you to quickly enter a number to dial without having
to know the nitty-gritty modem command.  Simply enter the number to dial and
press Enter.  The dialing directory will disappear and the modem dials the
number.

If you do not get a connection, the Manual Dial feature remembers the last
number entered.  You can then press Alt-D/M and press Enter to redial the
last number entered manually.
!Topic 103 Tag Multiple Entries  (Alt-D/T)
!NoIndex

Tag Multiple tags entries based on number, number range, or contents.
Prefix codes may be inserted or changed on the fly.  To tag entries, type
the entry numbers separated by spaces:

       12 19 34 77

To tag entries based on their textual content, precede the text with the
letter T:

       TChicago T312

To tag an entry and add a prefix on the fly, precede the entry number with
the letter P:

       P32A   add suffix A to entry 32
       PC45   add prefix C to entry 45
       PD78E  add prefix D and suffix E to entry 78

NOTE: Tagging with prefix modifiers updates the directory, and a backup file
is created prior to tagging.
!Topic 104 Find Text  (Alt-D/F)
!NoIndex

Find Text is used to search the Directory and Attached Notes for a
specific text string.  The first matching entry will become the current
entry.  If this is not the entry you were looking for you can use the
A-Find Again command.  The search will resume with the entry
immediately following the current entry.

NOTE: If the matching text is found in an Attached Note, Qmodem will display
a status window to that effect. The N command may then be used to view the
contents of the note where the match was found.
!Topic 105 Print FON Book (Alt-D/P)
!NoIndex

Print 132/80 produces a listing of the Dialing Directory on a selected
device or to a file.  Pressing ^P will print all directory fields using
132 columns, while P will print selected fields using an 80-column
format.

To print the listing, reply PRN or LPT1 to the displayed prompt.  To
direct the listing to disk, enter a valid DOS filename.  Entries with
blank Name fields will not be listed.
